{
  "On a horizontal surface, what does the normal force equal for a stationary object?": "",
  "The color and visual appearance of the surface, because darker or painted surfaces generate more friction than lighter-colored surfaces at the molecular level": "",
  "The weight of the object (N = mg)": "",
  "Air molecules pushing against the surfaces and creating a thin layer of resistance between them, since atmospheric pressure is the primary cause of surface friction": "",
  "Gravity pulling the two objects together with a force proportional to their combined masses, since gravitational attraction is the fundamental source of all friction": "",
  "On a horizontal surface with no other vertical forces, the normal force balances the weight: N = mg.": "",
  "In which direction does the normal force act?": "",
  "Static friction only exists on inclined surfaces and not on flat horizontal surfaces, because only the angle of an incline can create enough frictional resistance force": "",
  "Static friction and kinetic friction are exactly the same physical phenomenon described by identical coefficients, with no measurable difference in their force values": "",
  "Kinetic friction is always greater than static friction for any pair of surfaces in contact, because objects already in motion experience stronger resistance forces": "",
  "Perpendicular to the contact surface": "",
  "The normal force is always perpendicular to the surface. On a flat floor it points up, but on an incline it points perpendicular to the incline surface.": "",
  "On an inclined plane, what is the component of gravity parallel to the surface?": "",
  "mg sinθ, where θ is the angle of the incline": "",
  "mg costheta, which is the weight component directed perpendicular to the incline surface": "",
  "mg, the full weight of the object acting straight downward toward the center of the Earth": "",
  "mg tantheta, which is the ratio of the parallel and perpendicular gravity components": "",
  "The weight component along (parallel to) the incline = mg sinθ. This is what tends to make objects slide down.": "",
  "On an inclined plane, what is the normal force?": "",
  "mg tantheta, which gives the ratio of parallel to perpendicular weight components on the slope": "",
  "mg, the full weight of the object since the normal force always equals the total gravitational force": "",
  "mg sintheta, which is the component of gravity directed parallel along the surface of the incline": "",
  "mg cosθ, where θ is the angle of the incline": "",
  "The normal force on an incline = mg cosθ. It equals the perpendicular component of gravity on the incline surface.": "",
  "As the angle of an incline increases from 0° to 90°, what happens to the normal force?": "",
  "It stays constant": "",
  "It decreases — N = mg cosθ, and cos decreases from 1 to 0": "",
  "It first increases, then decreases": "",
  "It increases": "",
  "N = mg cosθ. At 0° (flat): N = mg. At 90° (vertical): N = 0. The normal force continuously decreases.": "",
  "Why does an object on a steeper incline tend to slide more easily?": "",
  "The object weighs more on steeper inclines because gravity is compressed into a smaller surface area, increasing the effective force per unit area on the object": "",
  "The gravitational acceleration is stronger on steeper inclines because the angle amplifies the gravitational field strength acting on objects placed on the surface": "",
  "Steeper inclines have more friction between the surfaces, because the increased slope causes greater surface deformation that produces more resistance to sliding": "",
  "The component of gravity along the incline (mg sinθ) increases while the normal force (and thus max friction) decreases": "",
  "As θ increases, mg sinθ (driving force) increases and mg cosθ (normal force, hence friction capacity) decreases. Both effects promote sliding.": "",
  "A 5 kg block sits on a 30° incline. What is the normal force? (g = 10 m/s²)": "",
  "43.3 N — N = mg cosθ = 50 × cos30° ≈ 50 × 0.866 ≈ 43.3 N": "",
  "86.6 N — N = mg sin theta = 50 times sin30 degrees = 50 times 0.5 = 25, then doubled to account for the incline factor giving approximately 86.6 N normal force": "",
  "50 N — N = mg = 50 N, because the normal force always equals the full weight of the object regardless of the angle of inclination of the surface": "",
  "25 N — N = mg sin theta = 50 times sin30 degrees = 50 times 0.5 = 25 N, using the sine component instead of the cosine for the perpendicular direction": "",
  "N = mg cosθ = 5 × 10 × cos30° = 50 × 0.866 ≈ 43.3 N.": "",
  "Can the normal force ever be greater than an object's weight?": "",
  "Yes — if an additional force pushes the object into the surface, the normal force exceeds the weight": "",
  "Only in zero gravity environments can the normal force exceed the weight, since without gravity the surface has no baseline force to compare against for the object": "",
  "No the normal force is always strictly less than the weight of the object, because surfaces can only partially support the gravitational force pressing the object down": "",
  "No the normal force always exactly equals the weight of the object in every situation, because the surface must precisely balance gravity and nothing more at all times": "",
  "If you press down on a book on a table, the normal force must support both the weight and your push: N = mg + F_push. The normal force adjusts to prevent penetration.": "",
  "What angle of incline would give a normal force of zero?": "",
  "45°": "",
  "90° (vertical) — N = mg cos90° = 0": "",
  "0° (horizontal)": "",
  "There is no such angle": "",
  "At 90°, the surface is vertical and there is no component of gravity pressing the object into the surface, so the normal force is zero.": "",
  "A box is on a ramp. Which force causes it to potentially slide down?": "",
  "Air resistance": "",
  "The normal force": "",
  "The component of gravity parallel to the ramp (mg sinθ)": "",
  "The component of gravity perpendicular to the ramp": "",
  "mg sinθ acts down the ramp and is the driving force for sliding. It is opposed by friction (up the ramp).": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes the normal force?": "",
  "A force that is always exactly equal to the object's weight in all situations, regardless of the surface orientation, applied forces, or any vertical acceleration present": "",
  "A component of the gravitational force itself, since the normal force is simply the portion of gravity that acts perpendicular to the surface of contact between objects": "",
  "A friction force that acts perpendicular to the direction of motion, resisting any tendency for the object to move sideways along the surface during sliding motion": "",
  "The contact force exerted by a surface on an object, directed perpendicular to the surface at the point of contact, preventing the object from penetrating the surface": "",
  "The normal force is a reaction force from the surface. 'Normal' means perpendicular. It adjusts to whatever value is needed to prevent the object from passing through the surface.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes an inclined plane?": "",
  "A perfectly vertical wall surface that has an inclination angle of exactly 90 degrees, forming a right angle with the horizontal ground surface beneath the object": "",
  "A perfectly horizontal floor surface with zero inclination angle, where the normal force equals the full weight of any object resting on its flat level surface": "",
  "Any curved surface such as a sphere, cylinder, or parabola, where the inclination angle varies continuously from one point to another along the curvature path": "",
  "A flat surface tilted at an angle to the horizontal that allows the analysis of motion along and perpendicular to the surface using resolved weight components": "",
  "An inclined plane is one of the simple machines. In physics problems, it allows us to decompose gravity into components parallel and perpendicular to the surface.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes the angle of inclination?": "",
  "The angle of friction between the surfaces, defined as the arctangent of the coefficient of kinetic friction for the materials in contact on the inclined surface": "",
  "The angle between the applied pushing force and the surface of the incline, which determines how much of the applied force contributes to motion along the slope": "",
  "The angle (θ) between the inclined surface and the horizontal, which determines the split of gravitational force into parallel and perpendicular components": "",
  "The angle between the object and the vertical direction, which is the complement of the inclination angle and determines the perpendicular component of gravity": "",
  "θ is measured from the horizontal to the surface of the incline. It determines: parallel gravity = mg sinθ, perpendicular gravity = mg cosθ.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes the parallel component of gravity on an incline?": "",
  "mg costheta, which is the component of gravitational force directed perpendicular to the incline surface and balanced by the normal force at the contact point": "",
  "The normal force that the surface exerts on the object, which acts perpendicular to the incline surface and prevents the object from falling through the material": "",
  "The component of gravitational force directed along the surface of the incline, equal to mg sinθ, which tends to pull the object down the slope": "",
  "The total weight of the object (mg), directed straight downward, which acts on the object regardless of the surface angle or any other forces applied to it": "",
  "The parallel component (mg sinθ) acts along the slope surface, either accelerating the object downhill or being balanced by friction.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes the perpendicular component of gravity on an incline?": "",
  "The component of gravitational force directed into the surface of the incline, equal to mg cosθ, which is balanced by the normal force": "",
  "mg sintheta, which is the component directed along the surface of the incline that tends to accelerate the object down the slope against any friction force present": "",
  "The force that pulls the object down the slope parallel to the surface, equal to mg sintheta, which is the driving force responsible for making objects slide down": "",
  "The friction force acting on the incline surface, directed opposite to the motion or tendency of motion, with magnitude equal to the friction coefficient times normal force": "",
  "The perpendicular component (mg cosθ) pushes the object into the surface. The normal force equals this component: N = mg cosθ (when no other forces act perpendicular to the surface).": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes the critical angle of an incline?": "",
  "The steepest angle at which an object can remain stationary on an incline, determined by θ_c = arctan(μ_s) — beyond this angle, static friction cannot prevent sliding": "",
  "Always exactly 45 degrees for any combination of materials and surfaces, since the critical angle is a universal constant that does not depend on surface properties": "",
  "The angle at which the object launches off the incline surface and becomes airborne, losing contact with the ramp and entering projectile motion through the air": "",
  "The angle at which the normal force becomes exactly zero, which only occurs at 90 degrees when the surface is perfectly vertical and provides no perpendicular support": "",
  "At the critical angle, mg sinθ = μ_s × mg cosθ → tanθ_c = μ_s. This is independent of mass. Beyond this angle, the object slides.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes weight decomposition on an incline?": "",
  "The gradual physical breakdown and deterioration of an object over extended time due to environmental exposure, corrosion, fatigue, and other degradation processes": "",
  "The physical process of dividing an object's mass into separate smaller parts, distributing the material evenly among multiple pieces for easier handling and transport": "",
  "The procedure of measuring an object's weight on different planets to determine how gravitational field strength varies across different locations in the solar system": "",
  "The process of resolving the gravitational force vector into two perpendicular components: one parallel to the incline (mg sinθ) and one perpendicular to the incline (mg cosθ)": "",
  "Weight decomposition uses trigonometry to split gravity into useful components aligned with the incline. This simplifies the analysis of forces and acceleration on the ramp.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes the free-body diagram for an object on an incline?": "",
  "A diagram showing the object isolated with its weight (straight down), normal force (perpendicular to surface), friction (along surface), and any applied forces, typically using tilted axes aligned with the incline": "",
  "A velocity-time graph that shows how the speed of the object changes as it moves along the incline surface, with slope representing the acceleration due to gravity": "",
  "A bird's-eye photograph of the incline taken from directly above, showing the spatial layout of the ramp and the positions of all objects on its surface from overhead": "",
  "A diagram that shows all objects present on the incline simultaneously, including the ramp structure itself, any pulleys, ropes, and the surrounding environment": "",
  "The FBD for an incline problem typically uses tilted axes (x along the slope, y perpendicular) so that the normal force and friction align with axes, requiring only the weight to be decomposed.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes mechanical advantage of an inclined plane?": "",
  "The angle of the incline measured in degrees or radians, which determines how steeply the surface is tilted relative to the horizontal ground reference plane": "",
  "The normal force divided by the total weight of the object, giving a dimensionless ratio that characterizes the perpendicular force balance on the incline surface": "",
  "The ratio of the weight of an object to the force needed to move it up the incline — a longer, gentler incline requires less force but over a greater distance": "",
  "The coefficient of friction of the incline surface material, which characterizes how rough or smooth the surface is and determines the maximum friction force available": "",
  "For a frictionless incline: Force needed = mg sinθ, which is less than mg. The longer the incline (smaller θ), the smaller the force needed, but the greater the distance traveled. Work = same.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes equilibrium on an incline?": "",
  "The condition where the net force on an object on an incline is zero — gravity's parallel component is balanced by friction (and/or an applied force), and the normal force balances the perpendicular component": "",
  "An object that has reached the bottom of the incline after sliding the entire length, completing its journey from the top starting position to the ground level below": "",
  "An object that is sliding down the incline at constant velocity, experiencing equal gravitational pull and friction force while maintaining a steady nonzero speed": "",
  "Any object placed anywhere on an incline regardless of the forces acting on it, since merely being on a tilted surface qualifies the object as being in equilibrium": "",
  "Equilibrium: ΣF_parallel = 0 (friction or applied force balances mg sinθ) and ΣF_perpendicular = 0 (N = mg cosθ). The object is either stationary or moving at constant velocity along the incline.": "",
  "A 10 kg box sits on a frictionless 30° incline. What is its acceleration down the slope? (g = 10 m/s²)": "",
  "5 m/s² — a = g sinθ = 10 × sin30° = 10 × 0.5 = 5 m/s² down the incline": "",
  "10 m/s squared — a = g = 10 m/s squared, because on any frictionless incline the full gravitational acceleration acts on the object regardless of the incline angle": "",
  "8.66 m/s squared — a = g costheta = 10 times cos30 = 10 times 0.866 = 8.66 m/s squared, using the cosine rather than the sine for the parallel component": "",
  "0 m/s squared — without friction the block remains stationary because there is no friction force available to push the block down the slope surface": "",
  "On a frictionless incline: a = g sinθ = 10 × sin30° = 5 m/s² down the slope. The normal force and perpendicular gravity cancel.": "",
  "A 20 kg box is on a 45° incline with μ_k = 0.3. It slides down. What is its acceleration? (g = 10 m/s²)": "",
  "7.07 m/s squared — using a = g sintheta only: a = 10 times sin45 = 10 times 0.707 = 7.07 m/s squared, ignoring the friction contribution to the net force": "",
  "a = g(sinθ − μ_k cosθ) = 10(sin45° − 0.3cos45°) = 10(0.707 − 0.212) ≈ 4.95 m/s²": "",
  "10 m/s squared — the acceleration equals g = 10 m/s squared because on a 45 degree incline the full gravitational acceleration acts along the slope surface": "",
  "2.12 m/s squared — using a = g times mu costheta: a = 10 times 0.3 times 0.707 = 2.12 m/s squared, using only the friction component of the total force": "",
  "a = g(sinθ − μ_k cosθ) = 10(0.707 − 0.3 × 0.707) = 10(0.707 − 0.212) = 10 × 0.495 = 4.95 m/s².": "",
  "A person pushes a 15 kg box up a 20° frictionless incline with a force applied parallel to the incline. What minimum force is needed to push it up at constant velocity?": "",
  "141 N — using F = mg costheta: F = 150 times cos20 = 150 times 0.94 = 141 N, because the perpendicular component determines the force needed to push up the slope": "",
  "51.3 N — at constant velocity, F = mg sinθ = 15 × 10 × sin20° ≈ 15 × 10 × 0.342 ≈ 51.3 N": "",
  "150 N — using F = mg = 150 N, because the full weight must be overcome to push the box up any incline regardless of the angle of the ramp surface": "",
  "25 N — using F = mg/number of incline degrees: F = 150/20 = 7.5 then adjusted to approximately 25 N based on the trigonometric correction factor": "",
  "Constant velocity → a = 0 → F = mg sinθ = 150 × sin20° ≈ 150 × 0.342 ≈ 51.3 N up the incline.": "",
  "A child slides down a playground slide (incline angle 35°) at constant velocity. What is the coefficient of kinetic friction?": "",
  "μ_k = tan35° ≈ 0.70 — constant velocity means mg sinθ = μ_k mg cosθ, so μ_k = tanθ": "",
  "0.57 — using mu = sintheta = sin35 = 0.574, because the friction coefficient equals the sine of the incline angle for objects sliding at constant velocity": "",
  "0.35 — using mu = theta/100 = 35/100 = 0.35, because the coefficient of kinetic friction is found by dividing the angle in degrees by one hundred": "",
  "1.00 — using mu = sintheta + costheta = 0.574 + 0.819 = 1.39 rounded to 1.00, because both trigonometric components contribute to the friction coefficient": "",
  "Constant velocity → a = 0 → mg sinθ = μ_k mg cosθ → μ_k = sinθ/cosθ = tan35° ≈ 0.700.": "",
  "You place a coin on a book and slowly tilt the book. At 22° the coin starts to slide. What is the coefficient of static friction?": "",
  "0.22 — using mu = theta/100 = 22/100 = 0.22, because the coefficient of static friction is found by dividing the critical angle in degrees by one hundred": "",
  "0.50 — using mu = sin(22) + cos(22)/2 = 0.375 + 0.463/2 = 0.5, because both sine and cosine contribute equally to the coefficient of static friction": "",
  "μ_s = tan22° ≈ 0.404 — the critical angle gives μ_s = tanθ_c": "",
  "0.38 — using mu = sin(22 degrees) = 0.375 rounded to 0.38, because the coefficient equals the sine rather than the tangent of the critical sliding angle": "",
  "At the critical angle: mg sinθ = μ_s mg cosθ → μ_s = tanθ_c = tan22° ≈ 0.404.": "",
  "A 50 kg person stands at the center of a 4 m long plank resting on two supports at each end. What is the normal force at each support? (g = 10 m/s²)": "",
  "250 N each — by symmetry, each support provides half the weight: N = mg/2 = 500/2 = 250 N": "",
  "1000 N total force applied at one end only, because gravity pulls the person toward the nearest support and all weight is transferred to that single support point": "",
  "500 N at each support — the full weight of 500 N is borne by each support independently, because each support must be capable of holding the person's entire weight": "",
  "125 N at each support — the weight is divided by four since there are two supports and the plank is four meters long, giving one quarter of the weight per support": "",
  "By symmetry (person at center), each support bears half the weight. N₁ = N₂ = mg/2 = 500/2 = 250 N.": "",
  "A 5 kg block on a 30° incline is attached by a rope to a 3 kg hanging block over a frictionless pulley. The incline is frictionless. Which way does the system move? (g = 10 m/s²)": "",
  "Cannot determine without knowing the friction coefficients, because without friction information it is impossible to predict the direction of motion on any incline": "",
  "The 3 kg block descends — weight of hanging block (30 N) > parallel force on inclined block (mg sin30° = 25 N), net force = 5 N, a = 5/8 = 0.625 m/s²": "",
  "The system is in perfect equilibrium and neither block moves, because the forces from the incline and the hanging block always balance each other on frictionless surfaces": "",
  "The 5 kg block slides down the incline pulling the 3 kg block upward, because the heavier block on the incline always dominates the motion of the connected system": "",
  "Incline block: force down slope = 5(10)sin30° = 25 N. Hanging block: weight = 3(10) = 30 N. Since 30 > 25, the 3 kg block descends. a = (30 − 25)/(5 + 3) = 5/8 = 0.625 m/s².": "",
  "An object sits on a 60° incline. Without friction, what fraction of its weight acts along the slope?": "",
  "100 percent of the weight acts along the slope, because on any incline steeper than 45 degrees the entire gravitational force is redirected parallel to the surface": "",
  "cos60 = 0.5 so 50 percent of the weight acts along the slope, because the cosine component rather than the sine component determines the parallel gravity force": "",
  "tan60 approximately 1.73 so 173 percent of the weight acts along the slope, because the tangent function determines the effective gravity along any inclined surface": "",
  "sin60° ≈ 0.866 — about 86.6% of the weight acts down the slope": "",
  "The parallel component = mg sinθ. As a fraction of weight (mg): sinθ = sin60° ≈ 0.866, so about 86.6% of the weight drives the object down the slope.": "",
  "A delivery worker pushes a 40 kg box up a 15° ramp at constant velocity. Friction coefficient μ_k = 0.25. What force must she apply parallel to the ramp? (g = 10 m/s²)": "",
  "400 N — the force equals the full weight: F = mg = 40 times 10 = 400 N, because pushing up any incline requires overcoming the object's complete weight value": "",
  "103 N — the force equals mg sintheta alone: F = 400 times 0.259 = 103 N, because friction acts in the same direction as the push and helps move the box upward": "",
  "F = mg sinθ + μ_k mg cosθ = 400(sin15° + 0.25cos15°) ≈ 400(0.259 + 0.242) ≈ 200 N": "",
  "97 N — the force equals mg times (sintheta minus mu costheta) = 400 times (0.259 minus 0.242) = 6.6 rounded up to approximately 97 N for the upward push": "",
  "Constant velocity → F = mg(sinθ + μ_k cosθ) = 400(0.259 + 0.25 × 0.966) = 400(0.259 + 0.242) = 400 × 0.501 ≈ 200 N.": "",
  "Two inclines of angles 30° and 60° are placed back to back like a tent. A 2 kg block is placed on the 30° side and a 3 kg block on the 60° side, connected by a rope over the peak. Both sides are frictionless. Which way does the system accelerate? (g = 10 m/s²)": "",
  "Both blocks slide down their respective sides simultaneously, because on frictionless surfaces all objects always accelerate downward regardless of any connecting ropes": "",
  "The 2 kg block on the 30 degree side slides down because the lighter block always descends first, since less mass means less inertia and faster downward acceleration": "",
  "The system is in perfect equilibrium and neither block moves, because the rope connecting them ensures equal tension that balances all forces on both sides of the peak": "",
  "The 3 kg block on the 60° side slides down — its parallel weight (3 × 10 × sin60° ≈ 26 N) exceeds the 30° side (2 × 10 × sin30° = 10 N); a = (26 − 10)/5 = 3.2 m/s²": "",
  "30° side: 2(10)sin30° = 10 N. 60° side: 3(10)sin60° ≈ 26 N. 60° side is heavier component. a = (26 − 10)/5 = 16/5 = 3.2 m/s² with the 3 kg block descending.": ""
